{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The user wants to solve a transcendental equation for the occupancy <n> in a mean-field lattice gas model. I need to delegate this to a computational tool/agent to perform the numerical root-finding.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "numerical_solver",
      "instructions": "Solve the following equation for <n>: <n> = 1 / (exp((epsilon * z * <n> - mu) / (k_B * T)) + 1). \n\nGiven parameters:\n- epsilon = -(k_B * T) / (2 * pi)\n- mu = 0.1 * k_B * T\n- z = z_h + z_v = 4 + 8 = 12\n- T = 300 K (Note: Since epsilon and mu are defined in terms of k_B * T, the absolute value of T cancels out in the exponent. Use k_B * T as a unit or set it to 1).\n\nStep 1: Simplify the exponent. Let x = <n>. The equation is x = 1 / (exp((epsilon/k_B*T * z * x) - (mu/k_B*T)) + 1).\nStep 2: Substitute values: \n  epsilon/(k_B*T) = -1 / (2 * pi)\n  mu/(k_B*T) = 0.1\n  z = 12\nStep 3: Solve x = 1 / (exp((-1/(2*pi)) * 12 * x - 0.1) + 1) for x.",
      "variable_overrides": {}
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Solve the transcendental equation for mean-field occupancy <n> using the provided physical constants and parameters."
}
```

